<h3>School and Learning</h3>
<p>This project was undertaken as part of a class I am taking at Oregon State University, CS290 - Web Development. The course covers topics such as HTML, JavaScript, and databases. The goal of this project is simple: to learn about an API I have no used before, and write a brief guide on how to use some of it.</p>

<h3>Any API</h3>
<p>We were allowed to choose any API out in the wild, except for ones that were overly simple. Years ago I earned a degree in Economics, so numbers and statistics have always interested me. You could say I like quantifying seemingly meaningless or random data. I wanted to learn about an API that could help me get access to large data sets, but that was also interesting to be. I spent a lot of time in the past going through data about people that I knew I wanted to work with something more fun/light.</p>

<p>I chose to use the Riot API because I had read about it before (though never used it). I am also a big League of Legends player myself. It offers diverse API calls, and can return things from simple data types to seriously huge JSON files. I knew that this was the one I wanted to be working with. <a href="https://developer.riotgames.com/">The Riot API</a> is free to use, and they do not present any paid options. From all of my readings into other APIs, this seemed odd considering all of the data that they could provide. There are some truly amazing sites out there that are created from this API - some do crazy tings with math and others show off the beauty and power of the web.</p>

